b'' b"i've read all of the followups to this, but i thought i'd go back to the" b'original article to make specific comments about the method:' b'' b'' b'' b'he has obtained the play by play records, in computer readable' b'form, for every major league baseball game for the past several years.' b'he devised an algorithm which i call "sum-over-situations", and wrote' b'a computer program to calculate every major league players contribution' b'using it. it works like this:' b'' b'look at every "situation" in every game in a baseball season. a' b'situation is determined by inning, score, where the baserunners are,' b'and how many outs there are. for each situation, count how many' b'times the team eventually won the game that the situation occured in,' b'and divide by the number of times the situation came up, to come up with' b'a "value" for that situation.' b'' b"this was first done by george lindsey in the late '50s/early '60s, and" b'reported in' b'' b'\tarticle:\tan investigation of strategies in baseball' b'\tauthor:\t\tgeorge r. lindsey' b'\tjournal:\toperations research' b'\tissue:\t\tvolume july-august pp. b'' b'later, pete palmer did the same thing using simulated seasons to generate' b'a larger set of data to avoid the kind of small-sample anomalies that other' b'people have worried about. he reported this in _the_hidden_game_of_baseball_' b'(with john thorn). gary skoog modified the method a bit and did some work' b'on what he called a "value added" measure based on these situational values.' b'his were based directly on marginal runs, though, not on win probabilities.' b'these results, as applied to the season, were reported in one of the' b'bill james baseball abstract books help me out here, somebody...)' b'' b'for example, a situation might be inning score runner on second' b'and no outs. there were regular season major league games last' b'year. (with the rockies and marlins, there will be more this year.)' b'say this situation came up in of those, and