d, for another and, finally, in the ninth to win the game by a score' b'of for a value of bob hit solo hr in plate appearances, and' b'was credited by your method with but what does' b'that mean? was bob responsible for the win? certainly not; the defense' b"is *always* responsible (if you include pitching in that), and bob wasn't" b'pitching. in fact, bob was only of the offense (which is a lot, but not' b'even close to furthermore, what about the other team runs? say' b'they all came on solo hr by fred; then fred was hitting hr to tie up the game,' b'which are just as valuable as hr to take the lead (see lindsey), and fred will' b'himself have accrued a good rating or so. so fred and bob combined have' b"amassed of a win in one game. there's clearly a problem here." b'' b'the only problem here is an insistance that these number mean exactly' b'how many wins the team has. first, we are using averages over many' b'seasons and applying them to one game. second, remember some players' b'performance take away from the chance of you winning. that is a' b'player who gets an out gets a "negative probability" in most cases.' b"thus, i'm not sure in any given game when you add up all the numbers" b'for a team who won that they will add up to in that game. sometimes,' b'they will add up to more then one sometime, less than one. also,' b"the pitchers' bad performances (giving up runs) may have given" b'them a large negative percentage for that game. also, any batter that' b'pulled an night would give large negatives.' b'' b'' b'' b'greg thinking about the right things, but his intuition is off the' b'mark. closers are enormously important. the total number of runs' b'value is outweighed by when they come, or are prevented from comming.' b'the doubling which greg allows is not enough.' b'' b"in another article, i proposed a test of this. we can predict a team's" b'won/lost record quite accurately by looking at how many runs *total* they' b'score and allow, without regard to when those runs score in the game. if' b'late runs are really more important than early runs, then looking only at' b'late runs should lead to a *better* predictor, right?' b'' b'no, but really only because you have a smaller sample size. i would' b'think however, that the number of runs you score in the first inning' b'would be just as good as a prediction as how many runs you score' b'in the last inning. and, realize something else a closer usually' b'comes in in a close situation, not a blow out. it is hard to argue' b'that any runs that a closer gives up in a game have equal importance' b'to those given up in the first inning. look, a closer giving up runs' b'often means a team will lose many games. on, the other hand a starter' b'who gives up runs often still leaves his team a chance to win. the' b'offence has many more outs to do something about. but, i am not' b'saying all late inning situations are equally important either. if' b'i am down runs in the ninth, it really does not matter how many' b'runs my pitcher gives up in the ninth.' b'' b"here's another thought experiment: apply this method to basketball. what" b'you find is that points scored in the first *half* of the game have almost' b'exactly no value, because no lead is safe with an entire half yet to play.' b'furthermore, the sub in off the bench who sinks the winning free throws with' b'no time on the clock gets a for the game, while the star forward who' b'scored points in the first half before spraining his ankle gets a zero.' b'' b'does this make sense?' b'' b'' b'no, but why would you assume that the teams probability of winning would' b'be before the possesion in which the free throws were made. look,' b'if you are down point with seconds left, there is a fairly high' b'probability that you will win the game if you are in possesion of the' b'ball. and, do not forget that somebody elses missed shots, turnovers,' b'fouls, bad defense, etc. caused a "negative chance" that the team' b'would win.' b'' b'from reading all of the discussion on this statistic, i feel that those' b'who critisize it to a certain extent are doing so out of an agenda.' b'at first look this statistic valadates clutchness. but, it really' b'does not. cluthness revolves around the idea that certain players' b'in crucial situation elevate their performance and others performance' b"goes down. i've never seen convincing proof that this really happens." b'so, if you assume there is no clutchness, then that means that except' b'for a lot of noice, this statistic has a positive association to' b'player performance. there is a way to get rid of the noice if you' b'do not believe in clutchness. certainly, we could find out what' b'the average value of a home run is for example. we may find for' b'instance, that a home run increases your chance of winning by b'on average while a strikeout decreases your chance of winning by b'i bet if this were done we would find that this statistic was just' b'as good as other statistics we have for predicting wins and losses.' b'' b'how do we evaluate relief pitchers? say john and sam have the' b"exact same pitching statistics (runs, earned runs, k's, bb's," b'etc.) both had exceptional numbers. john, however only pitched' b'in closer situations, while sam was a mop up man. who was more' b'valuble to their team? probably john. who was the better' b'pitcher? they were probably about the same.' b'' b'brian smith' 